[2] Italy
Date: Wed 22 Aug 2018 17:35 BST
Source: Express UK [edited]
https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1007012/west-nile-virus-veneto-italy-europe-world-health-organisation-west-nile-virus-symptoms


A 5th victim of the deadly West Nile virus has died in the Italian city of Padua bringing the total number of deaths to 9 in Italy and 43 across Europe, sparking panic among tourists. Italian officials confirmed the virus has so far infected 105 Italians since figures were updated on Wednesday night [22 Aug 2018] following the death of the 91-year-old man who has not been named.

On [14 Aug 2018], the figure was 84, meaning the total number of those infected has spiked by 21 in a week.

Though it is not known how many Europeans are currently infected with the virus, transmitted through mosquitos, the majority of cases are in Veneto, north western Italy.

Regional Councillor for Health, Luca Coletto, told Italian publication Il Messaggero: "We are facing a challenging situation, but it is not alarming, a hundred confirmed cases on a population of about 5 million inhabitants.

"The scientists point out that it is actually a virus with limited consequences, asymptomatic in 80 percent of cases and only in less than 1 percent able to evolve to the neuroinvasive form." The neuroinvasive form is the final stage of the virus before death. The latest victim was elderly and said to have been suffering from other unrelated illnesses, the publication reports.

Other victims have been from Treviso, Padua, and Verona and across Italy there are 34 patents seeking treatment in the most dangerous neuroinvasive stage of the illness. The 4 other victims that died of the disease were also pensioners and are yet to be named.

The 1st death caused by the disease in Treviso was recorded on the 31 Jul 2018, when an 86-year-old pensioner passed away in Legnago hospital. A week later, on 8 Aug 2018, the 2nd victim, an 89-year-old man from Este, the province of Padua, lost his life. After that, 2 others lost their lives in Verona.

The disease is transmitted by mosquitos with symptoms including fever, headache, tiredness, body aches, nausea, vomiting, and occasionally a skin rash and swollen lymph glands.

While the number of people infected with the virus has continued to grow in Veneto, some of the victims have not required medical intervention.

If victims do require medical attention then they are often given intravenous fluids, respiratory support, and prevention for secondary infections but there is currently no vaccine available for humans, the World Health Organisation notes.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to ECDC data of last week (https://ecdc.europa.eu/en/west-nile-fever/surveillance-and-disease-data/disease-data-ecdc), in 2018, as of 16 Aug 2018, 123 cases have been reported from Italy. However, the report in [2] above mentions 105 cases reported from Italy, with 5 deaths and majority of cases located in northwestern Italy.

Currently, there is no human vaccine against WNV. According to WHO guidance, in order to prevent infection, people in affected areas should follow the "4 Ds" of WNV prevention (http://www.euro.who.int/en/countries/italy/news/news/2018/8/west-nile-virus-infections-spike-in-southern-and-central-europe):
- Dusk: this is the prime feeding time for mosquitos and therefore when people are most likely to get bitten. Avoid outdoor activity at peak biting times.
- Dress: wear light-coloured long-sleeved shirts and trousers.
- DEET: use insect repellent that contains DEET (diethyltoluamide), strictly following the user instructions on the package.
- Drainage: make sure mosquito breeding sites (flower pots, water dishes, bird baths, and children's swimming pools) are drained so that they do not become breeding grounds for mosquitos.

In addition, people are advised to wear gloves and other protective clothing while handling sick animals or their tissues, and during slaughtering and culling procedures. - Mod.UBA]
